       <div class="box text">
        <a href="/galleries/tang-shipwreck" id="acmplaceholdercontent_2_ACMHomeGalleryRepeatItem_AcmHomeGalleryTitleOne_0">
         <h1>
          Tang Shipwreck
         </h1>
        </a>
        <p>
         Nearly 1100 years ago, an Arab ship bearing a precious cargo of ceramics, gold, silver set sail from the port of Canton. Just off the shores of Sumatra, near the island of Belitung, the ship sank, and remained untouched until discovered by chance in 1998.
        </p>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="gallery" id="acmplaceholdercontent_2_ACMHomeGalleryRepeatItem_AchHomeGalleryTwo_1">

         <h1>
          Scholars Gallery
         </h1>
        </a>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         For centuries, the scholar represented an ideal in Chinese culture. Great respect was accorded to individuals who could read classical texts, write and paint, play music, pursue academic studies, and demonstrate elegance and grace. Whether a civil servant, a successful merchant, or an overseas Chinese, learned individuals played a key role in Chinese culture.
        </p>
